## How to Show Experience

### ✅ Good (concrete, verifiable)
- "20+ years in IT"
- "Experience across marketing, UX, development, IoT, robotics, and management"
- "Worked on projects from IoT to internal tools"

### ❌ Bad (vague, unverifiable)
- "Hundreds of satisfied clients"
- "Award-winning developer"
- "Trusted by Fortune 500"

### Format for case studies (when added):
- Problem (1 sentence)
- Approach (2-3 sentences)
- Outcome (metrics if possible)

## Phase-Based Messaging (Critical!)

### Phase #1 - Discovery & Strategy
**What happens**: Discovery sessions with client → define users, value prop, journeys, metrics
**Deliverable**: Product Strategy document (problem statement, MVP scope, user personas, roadmap)
**Key message**: "Everything needed to start building" — tangible, standalone value

### Phase #2 - R&D & Prototyping
**What happens**: Solo work → translate Product Strategy into spec + prototype
**Deliverable**: UX mockups, technical specification, clickable prototype
**Key message**: "Something real to align on before we commit to the final build"

### Phase #3 - Execution & Delivery
**What happens**: Build architecture, implement with AI assistance, deploy
**Deliverable**: Production-ready first version online
**Key message**: "Ready to share with users, gather feedback, and validate in the market"

### Important framing:
- Show **continuity** between phases ("I translate Product Strategy into specification")
- Each phase has **standalone value** (can stop after any phase)
- Focus on **outcomes**, not process ("you get X" not "I do Y")
- Avoid suggesting failure/exit ("don't continue together" → "foundation for next phase")

## Insights from Development Process

### What works technically AND makes business sense
- Multi-disciplinary background allows holistic design
- Systems thinking = design whole solutions, not just apps
- User flows + data flows + analytics + admin + deployment = coherent blueprint
- Fast R&D with AI agents under human supervision
- Rough-but-usable prototypes > perfect mockups (faster validation)

### Value proposition clarity
- **Not**: "All-in-one architect" (sounds like generalist)
- **Yes**: "Bootstrap partner" with clear 3-phase process
- **Not**: "I do everything" (no perceived depth)
- **Yes**: "I design end-to-end solutions with systems-thinking approach"

### Deliverables = credibility
- Always name **concrete outputs** (docs, prototypes, deployed code)
- Product Strategy document = justifies Phase 1 payment
- Clickable prototype = proof of progress in Phase 2
- Production-ready code = clear handoff point

